# What is `@Autowired`?

`@Autowired` tells Spring to inject the required dependency automatically.

### Example

```java
@Autowired
private Computer comp;
```

Spring searches the IoC Container for a bean of type `Computer` and injects it.

This is called **Dependency Injection (DI).**

---

# What happens if multiple beans exist?

Example

```java
@Component
public class Laptop implements Computer {
}

@Component
public class Desktop implements Computer {
}
```

Both classes implement `Computer`.

Spring throws:

```text
No qualifying bean of type 'Computer'
expected single matching bean but found 2
```

To solve this, use **@Primary** or **@Qualifier**.

---

# `@Primary`

`@Primary` marks one bean as the **default bean**.

### Example

```java
@Component
@Primary
public class Desktop implements Computer {
}
```

Now whenever Spring needs a `Computer`, it injects the `Desktop` bean by default.

---

# `@Qualifier`

`@Qualifier` tells Spring exactly which bean to inject.

### Example

```java
@Autowired
@Qualifier("laptop")
public void setComp(Computer comp) {
    this.comp = comp;
}
```

Even if `Desktop` has `@Primary`, Spring injects the `Laptop` bean because **`@Qualifier` has higher priority**.

---

# `@Value`

`@Value` injects a fixed value into a field.

### Example

```java
@Component
public class Alien {

    @Value("23")
    private int age;
}
```

Spring automatically sets

```text
age = 23
```

during bean creation.

No need to write

```java
obj.setAge(23);
```

---

# `@Scope`

By default, every Spring bean is **Singleton**.

```text
One Bean
One Object
```

### Example

```java
@Component
public class Laptop {
}
```

Every time Spring returns the same object.

---

## Prototype Scope

```java
@Component
@Scope("prototype")
public class Laptop {
}
```

Now Spring creates a **new object** every time the bean is requested.

```text
getBean() → Laptop1
getBean() → Laptop2
getBean() → Laptop3
```

> **Note:** `@Scope` can be used on a `@Component` class or a `@Bean` method. It should not be used on setter methods.

---

# Why was the output like this?

```text
Alien Object Created
Laptop Object Created
Desktop Object Created
23
Coding....
Compiling from Laptop
```

### Step 1

Spring starts the IoC Container.

```java
new AnnotationConfigApplicationContext(AppConfig.class)
```

---

### Step 2

Spring scans the package and finds

```text
Alien
Laptop
Desktop
```

---

### Step 3

Spring starts creating the `Alien` bean.

```text
Alien Object Created
```

---

### Step 4

Spring finds

```java
@Value("23")
private int age;
```

and sets

```text
age = 23
```

---

### Step 5

Spring finds

```java
@Autowired
@Qualifier("laptop")
public void setComp(Computer comp)
```

It needs a `Computer` bean.

Available beans:

```text
Laptop
Desktop
```

Because `@Qualifier("laptop")` is present, Spring injects the `Laptop` bean.

```text
Laptop Object Created
```

---

### Step 6

Spring continues creating the remaining Singleton beans.

```text
Desktop Object Created
```

---

### Step 7

The IoC Container is now ready.

When

```java
Alien obj = context.getBean(Alien.class);
```

is executed, Spring returns the already-created `Alien` bean.

---

### Step 8

```java
System.out.println(obj.getAge());
```

prints

```text
23
```

---

### Step 9

```java
obj.code();
```

calls

```java
comp.compile();
```

Since `Laptop` was injected, the output is

```text
Compiling from Laptop
```

