# Complete Flow

```text
Application Starts
        │
        ▼
Read AppConfig
        │
        ▼
Read @Configuration
        │
        ▼
Read @ComponentScan
        │
        ▼
Scan Package
        │
        ▼
Find @Component Classes
        │
        ▼
Create Singleton Beans
        │
        ▼
Inject @Value
        │
        ▼
Perform @Autowired
        │
        ▼
Resolve @Primary / @Qualifier
        │
        ▼
IoC Container Ready
        │
        ▼
context.getBean()
        │
        ▼
Returns Existing Bean
```

## Key Points

- `@Component` → Marks a class as a Spring Bean.
- `@ComponentScan` → Tells Spring which package to scan.
- `@Autowired` → Automatically injects dependencies.
- `@Primary` → Makes one bean the default choice.
- `@Qualifier` → Injects a specific bean and overrides `@Primary`.
- `@Value` → Injects a fixed value into a field.
- `@Scope("prototype")` → Creates a new object every time the bean is requested.
- Singleton beans are created when the IoC Container starts.
- Spring cannot create objects of interfaces, so `@Component` should not be used on interfaces.
